<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910918-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>910918-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Fraser Inc. Paper Mill   Faces Proposed Fines   Of Nearly $4 Million</HL><DATE>09/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>RAW AND FINISHED PAPER PRODUCTS (PAP)</IN><GV>LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)</GV><RE>CANADA (CN)MAINE (ME)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Labor Department moved to fine a Mainepaper mill nearly $4 million, accusing it of more than 300safety and health violations.   Fraser Paper Ltd., a subsidiary of Fraser Inc. ofEdmundston, New Brunswick, Canada, was accused of havingunguarded mechanical and electrical equipment that posedsafety hazards and of failing to train employees adequately.Officials of the Department's Occupational Safety and HealthAdministration said they did a comprehensive inspection ofthe mill in Madawaska, Maine, after a release of chlorineearly this year resulted in the hospitalization of sevenworkers.</LP><TEXT>   Officials at Fraser Paper couldn't be reached for commenton the charges.   The OSHA administrator, Assistant Labor Secretary GeraldScannell, said the company knew the violations could lead toamputations, crushed bones and fatalities but didn't try toeliminate them. OSHA officials said 18 prior inspections hadbeen conducted at the mill, which had reported cripplingaccidents spanning a 17-year period. About three-quarters ofthe proposed fine of $3,928,500 was levied for 133 instancesof unguarded machinery.   The mill employs about 1,200 people and produces coatedand uncoated catalog paper for sale throughout the world.Fraser has 15 working days to contest the charges andproposed penalties before the independent Occupational Safetyand Health Review Commission.</TEXT></DOC>